In two previous threads there was some discussion about kitsune
https://desuarchive.org/trash/thread/44409477
https://desuarchive.org/trash/thread/44392295

Just wanted to mention to the writer considering kitsune stories, there's a lot of info available. In particular, even in Japan there are a number of different kitsune, so don't confuse a 'normal' kitsune with an Inari, for example. China, Korea and India all have their versions. A fair bit of kitsune & related lore seems to be traced back to Buddhist origins and the way spiritual power is viewed and manifested as Buddhism became core to other religions and spiritual systems, such as Shintoism.

Here's a few links to give an idea, including some of the contradictions. I like the short summary of the story in this first link as a quick window into numerous possbilities.

https://yokai.com/masakigitsune/ (follow related links on this page for many other translated nuggets of Japanese mythology)

https://mythus.fandom.com/wiki/Kitsune
https://medium.com/@kaldibeta/7-types-of-kitsune-spirits-in-japan-4061b87fa8f0

The mythology and terms on those pages should yield up a very rich mine of search engine strings to track down much, much more. In summary, you can pick and choose in a sort of Create Your Own Adventure what you want to focus on and ignore & imply the rest.

https://japan-avenue.com/blogs/japan/kitsune
>According to the Japanese imagination, when rain starts falling on a sunny day, it means that a marriage between a kitsune and a human has taken place. This is usually a sign of good omen. The children born from this union would have a human appearance with some powers inherited from their mother. One of the most popular legends is that of Kuzunoha.

Thought this highly relevant to the sister that is married to a human.

Have you ever seen the rain
coming down on a sunny day?
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-VaJ47l1y9Y

Anonymous Mon 03 Jan 2022 05:56:24 No.44445087 Report
Quoted By: >>44445973
>>44444075
Well, there are three overarching classes of species: those that usually live above ground but can navigate the tunnels (a terrier would fit this bill), those that spend time both above and below ground (many mammals), and those that are unlikely to visit the surface (and thus have several advantages). Some would only have access to hand-to-hand combat, and the types of weapons would vary by where you'd normally live.
The general combat I had in mind follows the story - don't, unless you can handle the results. You're more likely to ambush or pull off a samurai-style "kill as you unsheath the sword" move. Your location is always the best weapon. Use your skills and possessions to devastating effect.

Thinking about that part of the setting in terms of a game really let me put reasonable limits on things. You wouldn't want to make it too wild down there or you risk detection. That could result in a choice exit point or path becoming permanently unavailable. One option is to use missions to build up diplomatic contacts and influence both above and below ground. Or you could be a nightmare of the dark and play to survive, eradicating others for territory with predatory efficiency.

I'd note on all new chapters revision dates for any previous chapters since previous chapters posted. Maybe even use a version system, such as

Current Ch. 11 ver 1.00 2022-01-03
- Ch. 03 updated to ver 1.20 2021-09-27
- Ch. 06 updated to ver 1.35 2021-08-20
- Ch. 07 updated to ver 2.11 2021-12-13
- Ch. 09 updated to ver 1.73 2022-01-02

Skip notification for minor typo fixes, but track your version numbers for them in your own records for things published that went live on the Internet. Any content change, such as rewriting even one sentence, and post notification with new chapter. Increment by full numeral if "major rewrite" (such as plot change/retcon), by decimal 0.10 if section rewritten for clarity/grammar/flow, by decimal 0.01 if typo, missing/wrong word fixed, etc. Any chapter you revise can have all the major version changes & their dates, just add that info as you do it.

If you want to be anal, keep a Change Log (that describes the changes, maybe with Author Notes on why) in it's own file and link to it so people can decide if it's worth their time to re-read for a single line of dialogue change, or maybe three paragraphs were substantially rewritten.

When you get to the final conclusion and the entire story is finished and all rewrites/revisions are completed & proofread to your satisfaction, then publish the entire story as a single work. Decide if you want to take down all the individual chapters at that point, or leave them in place for whatever reason with a note at the top of file for each linking to the completed work.
